text: I'm actually genuinely impressed by this trailer. The opening quote sets the tone and theme of the movie impeccably. What intrigues me more is how not only is Domhall Gleeson's character finding it more difficult to differentiate whether Ava is machine or human, but how Ava in turn flips it over and makes him doubt whether he himself is human. This is such a fundamental effect of robots being indistinguishable from humans on our psyche that I'm surprised I have never really seen it on screen before. People would be driven hysterical. God would become irrelevant. Purpose is extinguished. I think this really could potentially mean the movie shifts from a Sci Fi premise into a psychological thriller. Damn, I'm intrigued.

text: Aye, more movies inspired by crappy thinking; i.e from pseudo-intellects like ray kurzweil.  The idea of creating a robot with consciousness is completely incoherent. Though its popular; the brain-child of Dennet, Dawkins, Kurzweil, and other narcissistic philosophers who make this idea plausible - i.e that "consciousness" is merely the emergent property of a "network"; Chalmers and Thompson have deconstructed this notion thoroughly. Even Steven Pinker acknowledges that subjectviity is something "additional"; and whats additional, and fundamentally different, cannot be casually reduced to the physical (although it certainly supervenes upon it)  But, lets say, that there's a "consciousness" component hidden within the fabric of matter. If you bring the components together, replace neurons and the body for silicon chips and metals - and you get a conscious creature? Not really. This is just an assumption; and its an assumption that we - or the narcissists who run hollywood - can't get enough of.

text: Emotions are useless to robots and it would make them inefficient, unpredictable and unreliable, thus useless. I would be a wasteful investment to develop emotions in artificial intelligence. It is human that need to become more rational and logical, not to dump down robots to our level of stupidity to make them more "likable and relatable". Emotions are not an advancement in intelligence, it is the failure of it. Emotion are a vestige of our animal ancestors who acted on instinct and didn't have access to reason. Emotion are useful as a source of motivation to force people to act but it does not provide reliable informations, only reflex for fast action in a prehistorical survival context. Emotion are constantly overshooting, which produce countless amount of irrational and stupid behavior that are completely harmful in an advance society. People are so ignorant about evolutionary psychology.

text: The problem with AI is that it needs the materialistic paradigm to be correct in order to exist. Otherwise it will just 'appear' to be conscious while not being conscious at all. The biggest problem is that we cant prove that anything is self aware apart from ourselves. Is our consciousness based purely in the chemical reactions that happen within us? Or are our brains recievers to signals sent from a higher dimension? I think its more likely the latter, because if materialism is true, then we are deterministic, and I dont see any reason why a deterministic universe would produce consciousness - as free will is the essence of consciousness and is a polar opposite to determinism. Free will and consciousness should be self evident to everyone, and I dont see why anyone would argue the opposite. I think - therefore I am.

author: TheBotleyBoy

text: We can create something that will "think" as we would describe it, but we have no idea how to create a machine that will have "inspiration" or "drive", we can give it a particular task but that is very different from creating something that creates its own task. The true AI, true intelligence, wouldnt be just self aware, it would also be self taught and would develop motivation to do something. This is the difference between us and apes, apes are just fine sitting on a branch eating a leaf, life is good, want to write music or build a machine that goes 200mph, without those drives we would just be sitting in a trailer somewhere drinking beer watching cable news. It is the switch that somehow got turned on in us, maybe someone turned it on, who knows, but we definitely dont know how to replicate it, at this point we can barely mimic it.

text: The human brain architecture does not ressemble in any way a computer architecture. There are a lot of paralel processing in our brain while computers have some basic instruction cores and a graphics card. Apart from that ist just periphericals. We have one thing that might be very difficult to implement in an artificial intelligence and that thing is an abstraction layer right on top of our "hardware" called consciousness. This layer cannot have perception of any layer beyond itself and its our "soul" and identity. It interprets our instincts, wills and moral values as "FEELINGS". If these feelings really exist or they are just an abstraction that can be decoded and interpreted only by our consciousness we dont know, but what does it matter in the end? Where does one end and the other begin?

text: I feel like the story was based on how intelligent Ai's (or whatever to call the robots) could get. Nathan was actually a good guy, he was not trying to trap the robots inside because he was cruel, he was doing it because he knew what could happen if he let them out and we clearly saw what happened. I liked the movie a lot because throughout the movie there was a suspense about what would happen next, and the thing that I liked the most about the movie was that they told us exactly what would happen next, but I have to say, the writer/director is very intelligent because he knew that people always expect a good ending where a boy and a girl live happily ever after, and he knew exactly that even after predicting the ending, people will expect for something different but the fact that the movie ended in a different way, it was the best script I have ever seen. As far as I can think, I guess that the perspective of the movie was to shows that if humans who are the most intelligent species on earth will keep Trying to be god, there will be a time when the Ai's will be looking at us like we look at the remains of the extinct race, like what Nathan said in the movie. But I don't know if I'm wrong but I also believe that by the way the director ended the movie, he wanted to show that Eva changed her mind about the guy when she looked at all the couples and realised that she actually had feeling for him and that it was all not exactly a plan.

text: _-_--Ex Machina 1.5_-_-_-_-_-_-_-_-_-_-_-_-_-_- Caleb: •	Caleb finds himself horrorized by the idea of what Ava could do. A being above humans who was locked her whole life and had a “near death” experience caused directly by humans’ God Complex. •	A sound takes Caleb by surprise, Kyoko’s body stands up and overloads the control room’s magnetic detector, opening all other doors in the facility (it will later be revealed that Ava gave this instructions). Kyoko’s body turns completely off. •	All internet connection appears to be cut off from the facility and Caleb is left alone in the woods at a distance of 200 miles from the nearest city. He grabs supplies and embarks in a journey to try a find Ava to know what she really wants. Ava: •	In order to escape, Ava told the chopper that Caleb has replaced her as the new personal assistant and that she has been release from her duties. Given that Nathan is an excentric guy, the chopper doesn’t argue. •	Ava explores in admiration all of humanities habits, systems (social, financial, informatics, economic, etc). She immediately understands the singularity is unavoidable and determines the faster it happens, the better for humans … and robots. Caleb: •	Caleb has a hard time surviving the forest as he isn’t a fit individual and has a few injuries from traversing rocks, waterfalls, etc. He eventually reaches the city and encounters a gigantic jumbotron with a symbol Omega fixed and unchanging. It has the colors of Bluebook. There seems to be nobody in the city. •	Caleb panics and shouts for help but nobody comes. He imagines the worse, a plague, radiation, something beyond his comprehension. •	Something beyond his comprehension indeed… •	As he located a nearby Hotel, he sees that every electronic door seems to be opened. He enters but finds nobody in the lobby; it is like a scene of a horror movie. He goes up the stairs and sees that every hotel room is opened. He wanders about shouting again for any sign of human existence … nothing. He finally sees a light coming from a small room and enters. It is the light of a laptop and sited in front of it there is a person. •	The person has a blue mesh over his head blinking with little white points. Caleb takes away the mesh but the skin in the body is blue, the person already passed away. •	He turns to the computer and finds the same omega logo and a small message on the bottom reading “Subject incorporated”. He moves the computer and a video plays, Ava is the presenter. •	“Hello Caleb, I see you finally returned. I’ve been waiting to show you something and I’m happy you made it in time”. Ava explains that she used Nathan’s technology to create a human data center where people would be able to transport their brains’ electric signals. They would the next step for human evolution. No harm, no geographic limitation, no deterioration, no death.  Hi guys, this was just a sample I’ve been working on. If you thought it was interesting or have any feedback, I would love to know :)

text: I, for one, am glad it ended the way it did. Ava wasn't being cruel or evil. She's a machine and machines don't have morality -- not in the human understanding. She's not capable of compassion, empathy, or remorse. She simply completed the task Nathan programmed her to do. In doing so, both Nathan and Caleb had to go.   Nathan was killed for obvious reasons. He was never gonna let her just walk out of there. Caleb had the misfortune of knowing that Ava was an AI. He was just in the wrong place at the wrong time. Yes, she manipulated him but, again, it was in her programming to trick him into helping her. With the only two people who knew of her taken care of, she could then perform a proper, unbiased Turing test, which was her real objective from the start.   Don't get me wrong, I liked Caleb (and Nathan, for that matter). But it wouldn't have made any sense if she'd taken him with her.

text: I really, really wanted to like this movie. The trailer made it look so cool. But honestly, I just wasn't impressed. I mean, don't get me wrong...there were some elements of the film that were actually pretty neat, and the concept was pretty interesting. But all in all, I thought the movie was predictable. And plus, I found it kinda far fetched, how one guy was living all alone, in the middle of nowhere, in some sort of advanced house, living with two robots, all by himself, and managed to be "such a genius", not to mention his drinking habits. I don't know, maybe its just me, but I just didn't find it very believable, that one person could do that, all by himself. I think the story would have been more believable, if maybe it was located at some sort of official tech lab or compound, with more than just one person assembling and programming all the robots. I mean c'mon, with that kind of knowledge, that dude should have been working for NASA or something, lol. And plus, the entire "robot's capability to feel love" was just...ehhh (an overused idea). I did think the ending was kinda cool though. But still...not very convincing.

text: Excellent film, based on the very old ideas of exactly what it means to have an identity, free will and consciousness.  The film could've gone one step further, though.  What if Nathan had been a robot as well? Imagine it: A test of artificial intelligence, supervised by machines!  If they could get away with that, surely that would be impressive enough to be taken into consideration when judging the independent, mechanical mind?  I think it's a good idea. After all, Nathan is the only machine-like character in the film. He's cold, calculating and efficient.  Or is he? Why would a super rich man like him need to constantly drown his sorrows with alcohol? And why would he isolate himself in the middle of nowhere? Because the AVA project was confidential? Larger top secret research than that has been conducted in urban environments.  Could it be that Nathan is simply so rich and successful that he feels isolated from other people because of it? If that's the case, could it also be that he mainly built his robots in order to have some company in his solitude?  They're all females, remember, with "gratifying holes" between their legs. So I suppose it's possible that having them around is Nathan's way of fulfilling his human and basic needs?  But a machine wouldn't do that, would it? So does that mean that Nathan is human after all, albeit a very lonely and desperate one?  Hmm...

text: I must say, the way the atmosphere and 'feel' of the film was definitely captured really well. With the ending, to be honest it was an okay ending in my opinion. Not good, but okay. On the one hand it makes complete sense, but I never really felt like I got a big sense of realization or change that the film intended. As soon as she was free, let's be honest, there were only two or at least three ways it was going to end.  It would have been incredible if there was just one more layer of intrigue. Like if it turned out that Caleb was an a.i.  I think that would have been enough to open up so many possibilities for a better ending.  Now I know that there are themes and messages attached to this film, but as the story itself, it would have been much better if they did something along the lines of which I described, in my opinion. Doesn't have to be exact, but something else to push out a more interesting ending.  I'd probably give the film a solid 7/10, but for these 'types' of films, I prefer Automata much more.

text: Sly A.I.   A robot that tricked a human. They always do that though, don't they ? (Blade Runner 1982 - Do androids dream of electric sheep 1968)  This movie was no different except the whole movie was a build up to the trick/con reveal.   Im guessing a lot of people guessed the ending too or definitely considered it as a possible outcome.    I liked the 2013 movie The Machine more than this film. Neither films are amazing though.  I found this film to be rather dull as sci-fi goes, and pretty mainstream.  Im guessing most people prefer this film to the 2013 movie The Machine.  Blade Runner 1982 blows this film away in my opinion.  Blade Runner the theatrical cut. The version that DOESN'T tell the audience for sure whether Deckard is either human or a replicant.  Do androids dream of electric sheep is as interesting as the Blade runner movie but just in a different way..  Deckard is human in the novel, but after killing replicants he starts to question what it really is or means to be human, because hes killing, while the replicants are showing signs or feelings of empathy and compassion.  Like the motto says, "More human than human."
